{"slug":"competitor-nominations","graph":"companies","title":"Who else orbits the red-team cluster","sub":"the graph finds companies shaped like our 14 flagged rivals","headline":"The graph says <strong>Lasso Security, Knostic, Tessl</strong> compete with us but were never flagged, and ranks UiPath as our top buyer prospect. 14 of 20 prospects and 8 of 10 rivals keep their spot when the 70 unverified edges are added.","prose":{"intro":"<p>We flagged 14 companies as competitors by hand. This panel asks the graph two questions. Which <em>buyers</em> sit closest to that red-team cluster? Those are prospects. And which unflagged companies does the graph treat as one of the pack? Those are rivals we may have missed.</p>","how":"<p>The idea: give the graph a few examples and ask for more like them. Each company gets a position computed from the verified edges alone, placed so that companies with similar connections sit near each other. Each of the 14 rivals then ranks every candidate by distance, and we merge the lists with two standard rank-combining rules. Where both rules agree (17 of the top 20), we call it consensus and color it on the map. One warning from the data itself: the rivals do not form one tight cluster — their average spacing is 1.37× the market's, wider than 90% of random same-sized groups. That is why each rival votes separately instead of being averaged into a single query point, which would land in empty space. The “edges” column shows how much verified wiring backs each nomination; a rank built on 2 edges is a lead, not a verdict.</p>","method":"<p>Vertex nomination via adjacency spectral embedding (Fishkind, Lyzinski, Pao, Chen &amp; Priebe, <em>Vertex nomination schemes for membership prediction</em>, Ann. Appl. Stat. 2015). ASE of the binarized undirected company graph, verified edges only (456 unique pairs from 460 verified records; diagonal augmentation; Zhu–Ghodsi elbow picked d=4; svd_seed=0). The graph is disconnected — 13 companies have no verified edge, embed at exactly the origin, and are excluded from the candidate pool as artifacts. Per-seed Euclidean distance ranks are fused by Borda count and by reciprocal-rank fusion (Cormack, Clarke &amp; Büttcher, SIGIR 2009; k=60), ties broken lexicographically. Tightness null: 1000 random seed-sized subsets of embedded companies. Sensitivity: the pipeline re-run on all 523 unique pairs including unverified edges, same candidate pool; a row “survives” if it stays in its table.</p>"},"caveat":"All the seeds are security-eval vendors, so the buyer list means “wired into the red-team world,” not “ready to buy.” The method cannot see us either: AoC ranks #95 of 161 because it has only 2 verified edges. Check the edges column before acting on a thin nomination. And note who is missing: no bank ranks anywhere near the cluster yet.","inputs":{"companies":{"nodes":188,"edges":530}},"data":{"tightness":{"seed_mean":0.572,"market_mean":0.418,"ratio":1.368,"null_pctile":0.897},"prospects":[{"id":"uipath","label":"UiPath","vertical":"enterprise other","borda":2,"rrf":4,"deg":3,"intensity":4,"survives":true,"flag":null,"persona":"VP of Automation / Chief Automation Officer (owns agent governance and reliability)"},{"id":"sap","label":"SAP","vertical":"enterprise other","borda":4,"rrf":10,"deg":3,"intensity":4,"survives":true,"flag":null,"persona":"Chief AI Officer / Head of AI Ethics & Trust"},{"id":"palantir","label":"Palantir","vertical":"enterprise other","borda":5,"rrf":3,"deg":2,"intensity":5,"survives":true,"flag":null,"persona":"Head of AI / CISO (and forward-deployed engineering leadership owning AIP deployments)"},{"id":"adobe","label":"Adobe","vertical":"enterprise other","borda":10,"rrf":19,"deg":2,"intensity":3,"survives":true,"flag":null,"persona":"Chief Trust Officer / VP Responsible AI"},{"id":"atlassian","label":"Atlassian","vertical":"enterprise other","borda":13,"rrf":23,"deg":2,"intensity":4,"survives":true,"flag":null,"persona":"Head of Trust / CISO"},